Social Determinants of Students in New York City Schools and Effects on Specialized High School Admissions¶

Ethan Chan ecc4001¶

https://github.com/conquer891/DSI_FinalProject

Introduction and Background¶

The specialized high schools in New York City (NYC) are a group of selective high schools administered by the NYC Department of Education. The founding three science schools, Stuyvesant High School, The Bronx Science High School of Science, and Brooklyn Technical High School were designated their specialized status in 1972, as a result of the Hecht-Calandra Act. The Hecht-Calandra Act established and preserved the founding schools statuses as specialized high schools in science and math for NYC. A uniform exam in mathematics and English, The Specialized High Schools Admissions Test (SHSAT), is administered to all eighth and ninth grade students who opt-in. The test is administered each year in October and November, and students are notified of their results the following March. Students must rank the schools they wish to apply to on the day of the exam. Admission is granted based on overall score results and school preference until there are no remaining seats. In the early 2000s, additional schools were added to the ranks, bringing the total number of specialized high schools to eight.

Throughout the years, there have been many attempts at both the city and state level to change the admissions criteria to these schools. These efforts have largely been unsuccessful. However, due to the plummeting number of black and Hispanic students admitted to the schools in recent years, the issue has once again entered the spotlight. Mayor Bill de Blasio, in addition to the citys teachers union, the United Federation of Teachers (UFT), have championed overhauling the admissions policy from a single test score to multiple measures which include socioeconomic index, race, and school performance.

Black and Hispanic students make up nearly 70 percent of NYCs public school system, but just over 10 percent of students admitted into the citys eight specialized high schools were black or Hispanic. In 2018, over 27,500 students took the admissions exam, 5,500 of which were black. Additionally, of the 4,800 students who were admitted into the specialized schools, only 190 students were black. The overall diversity of the specialized high schools (as of the 2017-2018 school year) paints a jarring picture. Black students make up 4.2% of the total seats, while Hispanics make up 6.1% of the specialized high school population. In contrast, Asian and White students make up 62% and 24.1% of the total number of seats, respectively.

This widening racial disparity requires further analysis. The aim of this project is to explore the factors which may play a role in the specialized high school admissions results.

Research Questions¶

  1. What are the demographic and socioeconomic makeup of middle schools across New York City?

  2. How do the social determinants and academic measures of students in NYC schools affect placement into specialized high schools?

  3. How can we employ unsupervised learning to determine which schools in NYC require the most assistance in order to increase specialized high school admissions?

Methods¶

This project made use of the PASSNYC School Explorer dataset published by PASSNYC. PASSNYC is a not-for-profit organization that is dedicated to broadening educational opportunities for NYCs underserved students. The School Explorer dataset contains demographic, socioeconomic and academic measures for all elementary and middle schools in NYC for the year 2016. The PASSNYC dataset was joined with the 2016-2017 SHSAT Admissions Test Offers by Sending School dataset, published by NYC Open Data, to analyze how social determinants of middle schools affect placement into the specialized high schools.

All analyses and visualization were performed exclusively in Python. The libraries used included: Pandas, NumPy, Seaborn, Matplotlib, and Scikit-learn.

The PASSNYC School Explorer dataset contains demographic, socioeconomic, and academic measures of each elementary and middle school in NYC for the year 2016. Upon loading in the dataset and performing some exploratory analysis, it was clear that this dataset required significant cleaning and preprocessing before further analysis could be done. A substantial number of measurement variables were recorded as objects or strings. Variables recorded as percentages included the symbol % in each observation, thus necessitating both the replace and astype functions to remove extraneous symbols and then subsequently converting the entire column to a float data type for further quantitative analysis. Additionally, a key variable of interest, School Income Estimate was recorded with dollar and , symbols, and recorded as an object data type. These symbols were removed and School Income Estimate was then subsequently converted to a float data type.

The PASSNYC School Explorer dataset also contained a considerable amount of missing data. Once the key measurement variables of interest were identified, imputation was performed based on the means of corresponding non-missing data. For example, schools which were missing school income estimates were imputed with the mean income of the corresponding zip code in which the school was located. This imputation was performed on all of the continuous and measurement variables of interest.

The 2016-2017 SHSAT Admissions Test Offers by Sending School dataset contains the recorded number of offers of admissions to specialized high schools in NYC, by school. Interestingly, schools with the lowest number of offers of admissions to specialized high schools were not recorded with a discrete count, but a range of 0-5 students. All 0-5 values were averaged (2.5), and then rounded up to 3 students as it is not possible to send 2.5 students to a specialized high school. Both the PASSNYC School Explorer and 2016-2017 SHSAT Admissions Test Offers by Sending School datasets contained DBN codes for each corresponding school. The DBN code is a unique code assigned to every school in NYC.

Both datasets were joined together on the DBN codes. A left join was performed, with the 2016-2017 SHSAT Admissions Test Offers by Sending School dataset on the left. Merging the two datasets together performed a very useful function. As we are only interested in NYC schools that can potentially send students to specialized high schools, the merging of the datasets effectively removed any schools that do not offer the eighth or ninth grades.

Several methods of data visualization, including bar charts, scatter, and regression plots were utilized in order to tell a cohesive story about how social determinants of schools affect placement into specialized high schools. A correlation matrix of key variables was used in order to determine which variables had the strongest associations with the number of offers to specialized high schools.

K-means clustering was performed on English Literature Arts (ELA) and math proficiency data to identify clusters of schools which need the most assistance. The SHSAT exam tests exclusively tests on English and mathematical aptitude, therefore it was logical to perform K-means clustering on the two variables above.

Results¶

Plotting the locations of middle schools across NYC and stratifying based on racial makeup of individual schools, it can be clearly seen that there are clusters of predominantly White/Asian and Black/Hispanic schools by geographic area or borough. Asian and White students make up a greater percentage of overall students in areas such as Northeastern Queens, the Upper West Side, and South Brooklyn. Black and Hispanic students make up a greater percentage of overall students in Southern Queens, North Brooklyn, and the Bronx.

The Economic Need Index (ENI) is a metric used to measure the socioeconomic circumstances of a schools population. A score is given to each school based on the number of students in the school eligible for free lunch, public assistance, or those who live in temporary housing. The scores range from 0 to 1. If a student is HRA-eligible or lives in temporary housing, the students ENI is 1.0. Plotting the locations of NYC schools and using a heatmap based on the ENI score of each school, it is quite apparent that the schools with the highest ENI scores are located in areas where Black and Hispanic students make up a large percentage of the overall school population.

The PASSNYC School Explorer dataset allows us a glimpse into the average racial makeup of schools in NYC, by city. Of note, the Bronx, Brooklyn, Manhattan, and Staten Island are reported as a whole by borough rather than the neighborhood, unlike in Queens. This is a peculiarity and could be a reflection of how mailing addresses in Queens are defined by individual cities/neighborhoods, whereas the other boroughs of NYC indicate the borough as the actual city. When plotting the average racial makeup of schools by City, as defined in the PASSNYC dataset, we can take a granular look into the racial makeup of individual Queens neighborhoods, but we lack the same granularity of analysis for the other boroughs of NYC. Queens neighborhoods, such as Cambria Heights, Elmhurst, Corona, and Saint Albans are predominantly Black or Hispanic. Conversely, Little Neck, Floral Park, and Broad Channel are predominately White or Asian.

When plotting a scatter regression plot on the count of offers to specialized high schools vs. racial and economic measures in the PASSNYC dataset, we can begin to see some trends. A higher ENI score is inversely correlated with the number of students sent to specialized high schools. This makes sense since students from poorer backgrounds tend to do worse in school, on average. Given that Asians are by far, the dominant race in the specialized high schools, it is not surprising to see a positive correlation to the number of offers to specialized high schools as the schools percentage of Asian representation increases. Lastly, we can also visualize the negative correlation between offers of admission as the Hispanic/Black representation increases at each school.

Using some of the quantitative variables available to us in the School Explorer dataset, we can output a correlation matrix of how different social determinants at each school correlate to the number of offers to specialized high schools. We can see that average ELA and math proficiency has a strong positive correlation to the number of offers given - this makes sense as the SHSAT exclusively tests on English and mathematical aptitude. ENI has a strong negative correlation with the number of offers given. Reflexively, as average school income estimates increase, the number of offers to specialized high schools also increase. We can also see a negative trend as more students at each school are chronically absent.

How can we identify the schools in NYC which need the most assistance in order to increased specialized high school admissions? The ELA and math proficiency at each school was used in combination with K-Means clustering to help us find our targets of interest. Our elbow curve helped us to identify the optimal number of clusters as 4. Once the K-Means clustering was performed, we are able to use the non-labeled clusters and join them back to our merged dataset. Mapping out the schools in NYC once again, now colored by cluster number, allows us to determine what schools need the most help in increasing ELA and math proficiency. Schools in cluster 0 have the most urgent need of additional resources. When comparing the map of schools, grouped by cluster, and the map of schools, grouped by ENI and percentage of Black and Hispanic students, we can see a clear parallel across the figures. Lastly, a table output of the cluster numbers, in addition to the names, locations, and ENIs of each school allows us to determine what schools and districts where additional funding or teaching staff can be best deployed.

Conclusion¶

The widening racial and wealth disparity in the United States gives cause for concern. We can observe this trend firsthand in our analysis into the social determinants of NYC schools and the role they play in specialized high school admissions. There is no single solution to inequality in our society. Narrowing the racial and wealth gap requires intervention at the governmental and policy level. With the exponential increase in data collection over the past few decades, we can employ data science to help us target where capital, and human capital, can benefit society the most.
